<h3 id="contents">Contents</h3>

<p>Your rÃ©sumÃ© is a living document. It needs to be updated as you gain new experiences at work. As you grow as a designer, you can also change the look to better reflect your current your skills.</p>

<p>Do your best to keep your whole rÃ©sumÃ© to one page. This will force you to get to the point and exclude extraneous details. Prospective employers will appreciate your brevity.</p>

<p>Include your complete contact information in a clear and obvious manner. If the document will end up in PDF format, donâ€™t include text URLs. Theyâ€™re ugly on the page. Link your text or link social media icons in the PDF.</p>

<p>You can include a statement right up front that says what youâ€™re looking for. <em>A job</em> is too obvious and bland. You can state how much you want to be part of the team, make change, etcâ€¦</p>

<p>When communicating your experience, donâ€™t exaggerate or leave things out. Include successes in previous jobs. If one of your listed successes was a team effort, say so. The ability to work in a team is actually a positive attribute.</p>

<p>If your previous jobs seem irrelevant to a position in graphic design, tell them which skills they gave you that will be of use to them. For example, if you worked at the returns counter at Canadian Tire, that would likely make you skilled at dealing with clients. You may even be able to tame the most rude, irate customers. Thatâ€™s an asset. Say that. Include travel, military, academics, accreditations, internships, volunteering and other life experience which would contribute to your value as an employee. Donâ€™t forget to state whether youâ€™re multi-lingual.</p>

<p>Be sure to address the recipient by name. Be formal about this. The commonly used <em>Hey, Iâ€™m Johnny and I love design</em> is too casual.</p>

<p>If youâ€™re going to use bullet lists, use action verbs to start each item, like these:</p>

<ul class="columns3">
	<li>authored</li>
	<li>brainstormed</li>
	<li>communicated</li>
	<li>conceptualized</li>
	<li>curated</li>
