<p>The issue here is that itâ€™s a no-win situation. Either you under-sell or over-sell yourself. If you state that youâ€™re an 9/10 with Photoshop, you better deliver 9/10. If youâ€™re 3/10, donâ€™t tell them!</p>

<h4 id="grin-and-bear-it">Grin and Bear It</h4>

<p>In my opinion, a really sharp looking mug shot is valuable. If you e-mail your rÃ©sumÃ© beforehand, the employer will recognize you when you go for an interview. Donâ€™t obscure your face in any way. Make yourself recognizable in the picture. Itâ€™ll make you more memorable. The only down side is if your photo is not professional enough. Have someone help you set up for the photo. Comb your hair and be well lit. You can take it with your phone.</p>

<p>Hopefully your rÃ©sumÃ© will only be one page long. That means the file size will be small. You can export your PDF with the <em>Print Ready</em> preset. Thatâ€™ll make the photo look sharp if they output on paper. Test it yourself.</p>

<h4 id="travel--photography">Travel &amp; Photography</h4>

<p>Who doesnâ€™t like a walk on the beach at sunset? Listing travel in your interest is obvious. Now, if you had an exceptionally remarkable travel experience, please tell us. Your four-day bender in Punta Cana doesnâ€™t cut it. As a teen, I sailed a tall ship across the South Pacific. Thatâ€™s something worth talking about, because it affected my growth as a person.</p>

<p>Unless youâ€™re actually a professional photographer, gear and all, avoid listing photography as one of your skills. First, itâ€™s offensive to all pro photogs out there. Second, you better be ready to deliver a full-fledged photo shoot. Third, weâ€™ve all taken that one incredible shot with our iPhone. One photo does not a photographer make.</p>

<h4 id="make-no-mistacke">Make No Mistacke!</h4>

<p>Itâ€™s crucial that you read and re-read your rÃ©sumÃ© to ensure itâ€™s error-free. Run your spell checker. Donâ€™t trust your spell checker! Have others read it. Have non-designers read it. Theyâ€™re not only reading for errors, they should give you feedback on the tone.</p>

<p>Achieving the appropriate tone in your writing is important. It can be very challenging. Your rÃ©sumÃ© is not really the place for humour. Your tone can be witty, but not flippant. It can be light-hearted, but not frivolous. It should be formal, but not overly-so. See how this isnâ€™t simple? If you have any doubts, just state things plainly.</p>

<p>It may be a good idea to have more than one design of your rÃ©sumÃ© if youâ€™re going to send it to designers vs freelance clients. Tailor your rÃ©sumÃ© for the recipient.</p>

<h4 id="your-cover-letter">Your Cover Letter</h4>

<p>You should have a cover letter. It needs to be addressed to the recipient by name, with their title and business contact information. Make the letter short. Research is needed here. If you can specifically target the skills theyâ€™re looking for, you can demonstrate that youâ€™re the best fit for the position.</p>

<p>If there was a job posting, answer the language in the posting in your cover letter.</p>

<h3 id="design">Design</h3>

<p>Your rÃ©sumÃ© is a professional business document. It shouldnâ€™t be origami artâ€”better simple and well executed than over-designed. Avoid clichÃ©s or contrived concepts thatâ€™ll be more of a burden on the employer. Youâ€™ll need to gauge the degree of creativity you put into your rÃ©sumÃ©. If you go overboard, the document overwhelms and confuses. If you stop short, you could be perceived as unimaginative or unmotivated.</p>

<p>How far do you go with your design? Thatâ€™s up to you. To start, your layout, typography and colour treatment needs to be flawlessâ€”even to a seasoned designer.</p>

<p>Design your rÃ©sumÃ© to have a consistent look with your web site and other social media platforms.</p>

<p>Avoid using a template. Youâ€™re a graphic designer. Design and build your rÃ©sumÃ© from the ground up.</p>

<p>Apply all the production skills you have. Resolution, file size and colour fidelity are all important.</p>

<h3 id="delivery">Delivery</h3>

<p>Paper? Who needs paper? Sharing a PDF file works well and saves trees. A responsive web page is really great too. Both is best! Either way, build it to be accessible. It has to work for recipients, no matter the screen and their abilities. Ok. Have a few paper backup copies with you.</p>

<p>Once youâ€™ve completed your PDF, the last thing you should do to it is open it in Acrobat. Hit âŒ˜-D.</p>

<ol>
	<li>Set the Navigation tab to Page Only if you only have a single page.</li>
	<li>Set Page Layout to Single Page.</li>
	<li>Set Magnification to Full Page.</li>
</ol>

<p>When the recipient opens your PDF, itâ€™ll be zoomed to show the whole page.</p>

<p>If you send out a resume in PDF format, make sure to name the file with your name. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Appleseed-Johnny-Resume.pdf</code>. The recipient may receive hundreds of them. They need to be able to find yours in the crowd.</p>

<p>You can e-mail your PDF as an attachment. You should also keep it in the cloud, in Dropbox or in Google Drive. Leave it in the same location in case someone goes back to retrieve it at a later date.</p>

